Here's a simple example of how you could implement a `ban` command as a slash command in a Discord bot using Discord.js v14. This will include setting up a new slash command and showing how to handle it when invoked. This bot example will be rudimentary and lacks certain features such as error handling, permissions checks, and logging for brevity. Ensure you replace `TOKEN` with your bot's token.

First, make sure to install `discord.js` if you haven't already:

```bash
npm install discord.js
```

Now, let's write the code:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');

// Replace 'TOKEN' with your bot's actual token
const client = new Discord.Client({ intents: ['GUILDS', 'GUILD_MESSAGES'] });
const token = 'TOKEN'; // Your bot's token

// Create a new slash command
client.application.commands.create({
  name: 'ban',
  description: 'Bans a member in your server',
  options: [{
    name: 'member',
    type: 'USER',
  }]
});

client.once('ready', () => {
  console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
});

// Event listener for when a command is invoked
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
  if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

  const command = interaction.commandName as string; // cast interaction.commandName from guild-only String to non-guild String

  if (command === 'ban' && interaction.options.has('member')) {
    console.log(`Ban command invoked for member ID: ${interaction.options.getUser('member').id}`);

    // Implement the logic for banning the user. For a bot with proper permissions, you can simply reject the command.
    interaction.reply({ content: 'User ban command is not allowed to be used by bots.', ephemeral: true });
  } else {
    interaction.reply({ content: 'Command not found.', ephemeral: true });
  }
});

// Log all error during interactionCreate as this helps in debugging
client.on('interactionCreateError', interaction => {
  console.error(`InteractionCreateError: ${interaction.message}`);
});

client.login(token);
```

To run this script:

1. Make sure you've set up a new bot following Discord's OAuth2 flow on the Discord developer portal.
2. Place this script in a file (e.g., `index.js`).
3. Run the script using Node.js.

Please note that bots typically do not have the permissions to execute a ban command unless they are configured to have moderation permissions or are part of a larger server setup where a specific role or owner of the bot can be an 'admin'. Remember to handle permissions and avoid letting your bot perform potentially harmful actions.

Creating a high-quality Cypress testing framework that utilizes Docker can greatly enhance repeatability, consistency and productivity. In this guide, we will also leverage Cypress's screenshot feature for capturing and saving visuals which could be useful for detecting UI issues.

The first step is to set up a Docker-based project.

1. Install Docker (https://www.docker.com/get-docker)

2. Create a Cypress project directory
```bash
mkdir cypress-docker-test
cd cypress-docker-test
```

3. Create a `package.json`:
```bash
npx cypress init
```

4. Specify the relevant dependencies in `package.json`:
```json
"devDependencies": {
  "cypress": "^11.2.0"
}
```

5. Update the `cypress.config.js` to setup Docker integration:
```javascript
module.exports = defineConfig({
  env: {
    baseUrl: 'https://example.com'
  },
  e2e: {
    specPattern: '**/*.cy.js',
    setupNodeEvents(on, config) {
      on('task', {
        savePage(filename) {
          // This task will run Cypress command to take a screenshot
          return cy.task('takeScreenshot', { name: filename, path: 'cypress/screenshots/' });
        }
      });

      return config;
    }
  }
});
```

6. Create a basic test to learn how Cypress works:
```javascript
describe('HomePage', () => {
  it('should have heading', () => {
    cy.visit('/');
    cy.get('h1').should('contain.text', 'Home Page');
  });
});
```

7. Save the screenshot in your test:
```javascript
it('should take a screenshot', () => {
  cy.visit('/');
  cy.savePage('homepage.png');
});
```

Next step is to set up the Docker environment.

1. Create a Dockerfile:
```Dockerfile
FROM cypress/base:11
COPY cypress.config.js /app/cypress.config.js
COPY ./cypress /app/cypress
WORKDIR /app
USER root
RUN chown -R cypress .
```

2. Create a docker-compose.yml:
```yaml
version: '3'
services:
  cypress:
    build: .
    environment:
      - CYPRESS_CACHE_FOLDER=/app/cache
      - CYPRESS_RECORD=true
    command: npm run open-browser -- --headless
```

3. Add `openBrowser` script in `package.json`:
```js
"scripts": {
  "open-browser": "cypress open",
  "docker": "docker compsee -f docker-compose.yml"
}
```

4. Add the `browsers` option to your `cypress.config.js` to let Docker know which browsers to run in:
```javascript
module.exports = defineConfig({
  "projectId": "${projectId}",
  "audioFilesPatterns": ["**/*.mp3"],
  "videoFilesPatterns": ["**/*.mp4", "**/*.webm", "**/*.png", "**/*.jpg", "**/*.tiff"],
  "env": {
    baseUrl: 'https://example.com'
  },
  e2e: {
    specPattern: '**/*.cy.js',
    screenshotsOnUse: {
      enabled: true,
    },
    video: true,
    browsers: ['chrome']
  }
});
```

5. Run Docker with your tests, your screenshots will be saved and Cypress will record a video:

```bash
npm run docker
```

Now, you will have a high-quality testing framework that utilizes Docker for a more consistent and repeatable environment and takes screenshots at each run. This will be quite handy when you need to debug issues due to UI changes.

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    html += "<p>"; // Start of paragraph tag

    // Remove leading '#' for headers
    for (size_t i = 0; i < markdown.size(); ++i) {
        if (markdown[i] == '#') {
            goto skip_header;
        }
        markdown[i] = ' '; // Replace '#' with space
    skip_header:;
    }

    size_t pos = 0;
    while ((pos = markdown.find(' ', pos)) != std::string::npos) {
        // Find next space, which is likely a paragraph boundary
        size_t endPos = markdown.find(' ', pos + 1);
        if (endPos == std::string::npos) {
            // If no more spaces, assume end of text
            endPos = markdown.size();
        }
        // Convert to header level, e.g., #header -> <h1>header</h1>
        int headerLevel = 1;
        while (markdown[pos - 1] == '#') {
            --headerLevel;
            --pos; // Move backwards to check for '#'
        }
        markdown.replace(pos, endPos - pos, "<h" + std::to_string(headerLevel) + ">");
        markdown.replace(pos + headerLevel * 2 + 4, endPos - pos - headerLevel * 2 - 4, "</h" + std::to_string(headerLevel) + ">");
        pos = endPos;
    }

    // Bullet list
    pos = markdown.find_first_of("-*["); // Find bullet list start
    while (pos != std::string::npos) {
        // Find next bullet list entry
        std::string entry;
        std::getline(markdown.begin() + pos, entry);
        size_t endPos = entry.find_first_not_of(" ", pos + 1);
        if (endPos == std::string::npos) {
            // If no more text, assume end of list item
            endPos = entry.size();
        }
        // Replace bullet list with <li>...</li>
        markdown.replace(pos, endPos - pos, "<li>" + entry.substr(0, endPos - pos) + "</li>");
        pos = markdown.find_first_not_of("-*[", pos + 5); // Skip to next list item
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Header 1\n## Header 2\n- Item 1\n- Item 2\n\nParagraph with **bold** and *italic* text.";
    std::string html = markdownToHTML(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}

