Problem Description: Write a function in C++ that calculates the longest common subsequence (LCS) of two strings without using recursion.

The longest common subsequence (LCS) problem is a classic computer science problem with applications in many areas including text comparison (diff), bioinformatics (sequence alignment), etc. This problem involves finding the maximum-length sequence of characters (or elements) that appear in both given strings, without reordering of characters (or elements within each string).

Here is an example problem instance:

Strings: s1 = "ABCDGH", s2 = "AEDFHR"

The longest common subsequence between s1 and s2 is: "ADH", with a length of 3.

Function Signature:

```cpp
std::string lcs(const std::string& s1, const std::string& s2);
```

Constraints:
- `1 ≤ s1.length, s2.length ≤ 1000`
- Both s1 and s2 consist of uppercase letters only.

Complexity Requirements:
- Time Complexity: O(mn) where m and n are the lengths of the two strings respectively.
- Space Complexity: O(mn) due to the storage of the LCS matrix for dynamic programming. However, optimizations can reduce space complexity to O(min(m, n)) by storing only two rows/columns at a time.

Write a function that calculates the longest common subsequence (LCS) of two strings. The algorithm should employ dynamic programming principles and avoid recursion. Do not use any external dependencies or libraries.

Example Solution:

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <string>

std::string lcs(const std::string& s1, const std::string& s2) {
    int m = s1.length(), n = s2.length();
    std::vector<std::vector<int>> dp(m + 1, std::vector<int>(n + 1, 0));

    for (int i = 1; i <= m; ++i) {
        for (int j = 1; j <= n; ++j) {
            if (s1[i - 1] == s2[j - 1])
                dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1] + 1;
            else
                dp[i][j] = std::max(dp[i - 1][j], dp[i][j - 1]);
        }
    }

    // Reconstruct the LCS
    std::string result;
    int x = m, y = n;
    while (x > 0 && y > 0) {
        if (s1[x - 1] == s2[y - 1]) {
            result.push_back(s1[x - 1]);
            --x;
            --y;
        }
        else if (dp[x - 1][y] > dp[x][y - 1]) {
            --x;
        }
        else {
            --y;
        }
    }

    std::reverse(result.begin(), result.end());
    return result;
}
```

